---
import CalculatorLayout from '../layouts/CalculatorLayout.astro';
import PaycheckCalculator from '../components/calculators/PaycheckCalculator';
import { TAX_YEAR } from '../lib/constants';

const title = `California State Tax Calculator ${TAX_YEAR}: All 10 Brackets`;
const description = `Calculate your California state income tax for ${TAX_YEAR}. See all 10 tax brackets (1%-13.3%), SDI withholding, and your total CA tax liability with deductions.`;

const faqs = [
  {
    question: `What are California's ${TAX_YEAR} income tax brackets?`,
    answer: `California has 10 progressive tax brackets ranging from 1% to 13.3%. For single filers in ${TAX_YEAR}: 1% on income up to $10,756; 2% up to $25,499; 4% up to $40,245; 6% up to $55,866; 8% up to $70,612; 9.3% up to $360,659; 10.3% up to $432,787; 11.3% up to $721,314; 12.3% up to $1,000,000; and 13.3% (with Mental Health Services Tax) on income over $1,000,000.`,
  },
  {
    question: 'What is California SDI and how much does it cost?',
    answer: `California State Disability Insurance (SDI) is a mandatory payroll deduction that funds short-term disability benefits and Paid Family Leave (PFL). In ${TAX_YEAR}, the SDI rate is 1.1% on all wages with no cap. This is deducted from your paycheck in addition to federal taxes, state income tax, and FICA.`,
  },
  {
    question: 'Does California tax capital gains differently?',
    answer: `No. Unlike the federal government, California taxes capital gains as ordinary income — there's no preferential long-term capital gains rate. This means long-term capital gains in California can be taxed at up to 13.3%, compared to the federal maximum of 20% (plus 3.8% NIIT). This makes California one of the most expensive states for investment income.`,
  },
  {
    question: 'What is the California standard deduction?',
    answer: `California's standard deduction for ${TAX_YEAR} is $5,540 for single filers and $11,080 for married filing jointly — significantly lower than the federal standard deduction of $15,700/$31,400. California also does not conform to all federal deductions, so your state taxable income may differ from your federal taxable income.`,
  },
];

const relatedCalculators = [
  { title: 'Paycheck Calculator', href: '/paycheck-calculator/california/', desc: 'CA paycheck breakdown' },
  { title: 'New York Tax Calculator', href: '/new-york-state-tax-calculator/', desc: 'Compare with NY taxes' },
  { title: 'Take-Home Comparison', href: '/take-home-comparison/', desc: 'Compare all 50 states' },
  { title: 'Income Tax Calculator', href: '/income-tax-calculator/', desc: 'Federal + state taxes' },
  { title: 'Capital Gains Tax', href: '/capital-gains-tax-calculator/', desc: 'CA taxes gains as income' },
];

const schema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'WebApplication',
  name: `California Tax Calculator ${TAX_YEAR}`,
  description,
  url: 'https://truetakehomepay.com/california-state-tax-calculator',
  applicationCategory: 'FinanceApplication',
  operatingSystem: 'Any',
  offers: { '@type': 'Offer', price: '0', priceCurrency: 'USD' },
  inLanguage: 'en-US',
};
---

<CalculatorLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  h1={`California Tax Calculator ${TAX_YEAR}`}
  intro={`Calculate your California state income tax across all 10 brackets for ${TAX_YEAR}. See how the 1%-13.3% progressive rate, SDI withholding, and California-specific deductions affect your take-home pay in the Golden State.`}
  faqs={faqs}
  relatedCalculators={relatedCalculators}
  schema={schema}
  sources={`California Franchise Tax Board (ftb.ca.gov) ${TAX_YEAR} tax rates and brackets, California EDD (SDI rates), IRS Rev. Proc. 2025-11 (federal brackets). Last updated for tax year ${TAX_YEAR}.`}
>
  <PaycheckCalculator client:load defaultState="CA" />
  <Fragment slot="content">
    <section class="border-t border-slate-200 px-4 py-16 dark:border-slate-800 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="prose prose-slate dark:prose-invert mx-auto max-w-3xl">
        <h2 id="california-income-tax-explained">Understanding California's Progressive Income Tax System</h2>
        <p>California's income tax structure is among the most complex and heavily graduated in the United States. With ten separate tax brackets ranging from 1% on the first few thousand dollars of taxable income to 13.3% on earnings exceeding one million dollars, the Golden State takes a significantly larger share of personal income than nearly every other jurisdiction in the country. This system was not built overnight. Decades of legislative action, voter-approved ballot measures, and budgetary pressures shaped the framework that workers and residents contend with today. Whether you recently moved to California for a tech job in Silicon Valley, an entertainment career in Los Angeles, or a biotech position in San Diego, understanding how these brackets interact with federal taxes and payroll withholdings is essential for accurate financial planning.</p>

        <p>The progressive nature of California's brackets means that income is taxed in layers. A single filer earning $80,000, for example, does not pay 8% on the entire amount. Instead, the first $10,756 is taxed at just 1%, the next portion up to $25,499 at 2%, then 4% up to $40,245, 6% up to $55,866, and 8% on the remaining dollars up to that salary level. This layered approach ensures that lower-income earners retain a larger percentage of their pay, while higher earners contribute more as their income rises through successive brackets. For an accurate breakdown of how these layers affect your actual paycheck, use our <a href="/paycheck-calculator/california/">California paycheck calculator</a> to see federal, state, and FICA deductions side by side.</p>

        <h2 id="why-california-has-highest-state-tax">Why California Has the Highest State Income Tax in America</h2>
        <p>California's top marginal rate of 13.3% sits above every other state in the nation, surpassing even Hawaii's 11% and New Jersey's 10.75%. The roots of this distinction trace back to 2004 when voters approved Proposition 63, now known as the Mental Health Services Tax. This measure imposed a 1% surcharge on taxable income exceeding one million dollars, pushing the top bracket from 12.3% to 13.3%. The revenue was earmarked for county-level mental health services, and the surcharge has remained in place ever since. What makes this particularly noteworthy is that the Mental Health Services Tax is not a temporary provision. It was embedded into the state constitution through the ballot initiative process, making it remarkably difficult to repeal.</p>

        <p>Beyond the Mental Health Services Tax, California's overall tax burden reflects the cost of governing the most populous state in the country. With roughly 39 million residents, extensive public university systems including the UC and CSU networks, a massive highway infrastructure, and some of the most generous social safety net programs in the nation, the state requires substantial revenue. The personal income tax is by far Sacramento's largest revenue source, accounting for roughly half of the state general fund in most fiscal years. This heavy reliance on income tax revenue from high earners creates significant budget volatility. During economic booms, California frequently runs surpluses, but during recessions, revenue can plummet by tens of billions when capital gains income and top-bracket wages decline.</p>

        <h2 id="mental-health-services-tax">The Mental Health Services Tax: California's Millionaire Surcharge</h2>
        <p>The 1% Mental Health Services Tax applies specifically to taxable income above $1,000,000 for all filing statuses. There is no phase-in or gradual ramp. Once a taxpayer crosses the million-dollar threshold, every additional dollar is taxed at the combined top rate of 13.3% at the state level. For context, a California resident earning $2,000,000 in taxable income would owe roughly $1,000 in Mental Health Services Tax on the second million alone, layered on top of the 12.3% standard top bracket. This creates a significant cliff effect where crossing from $999,999 to $1,000,001 triggers the additional surcharge on the excess amount.</p>

        <p>The revenue generated by this surcharge has been substantial. Since its inception, it has directed billions of dollars toward mental health services throughout California's 58 counties. The funds support psychiatric crisis centers, housing programs for individuals with severe mental illness, and community-based prevention initiatives. From a taxpayer perspective, the surcharge means that extremely high earners in California face a combined federal and state marginal rate that can approach 50% or more when you factor in the 37% federal top bracket, the 3.8% Net Investment Income Tax, and the 13.3% state rate. This combined burden drives many conversations about tax planning, income timing, and even relocation among California's wealthiest residents.</p>

        <h2 id="california-sdi-explained">California SDI: The Payroll Tax Most Workers Overlook</h2>
        <p>In addition to income taxes, California workers face a mandatory State Disability Insurance deduction that directly reduces take-home pay. The SDI rate for the current tax year is 1.1% with no wage base cap, meaning it applies to every dollar of wages regardless of how much you earn. This is a significant departure from how Social Security tax works at the federal level, where the 6.2% rate stops applying after earnings reach $168,600. A California worker earning $200,000 will pay $2,200 in SDI, while someone earning $500,000 will pay $5,500. This uncapped structure makes SDI progressively more expensive in absolute terms for higher earners.</p>

        <p>SDI funds two programs that many Californians rely on but few fully understand until they need them. The first is short-term disability insurance, which replaces approximately 60% to 70% of wages for up to 52 weeks when a worker cannot perform their job due to a non-work-related illness, injury, or pregnancy. The second is Paid Family Leave, which provides partial wage replacement for workers who need time off to bond with a new child, care for a seriously ill family member, or assist with certain military family needs. Unlike employer-sponsored disability insurance, SDI coverage is automatic for nearly all W-2 employees in California. If you want to see exactly how SDI affects your paycheck alongside federal withholdings, our <a href="/take-home-pay-calculator/">take-home pay calculator</a> includes California's SDI in its detailed breakdown.</p>

        <h2 id="california-vs-other-high-tax-states">How California Taxes Compare to Other High-Tax States</h2>
        <p>When comparing California's tax burden to states like <a href="/new-york-state-tax-calculator/">New York</a>, New Jersey, Hawaii, and Minnesota, the picture is nuanced. California holds the highest top marginal rate at 13.3%, but New York City residents face a combined state and city rate that can reach 14.776% when you add the 10.9% state rate to the 3.876% <a href="/nyc-tax-calculator/">NYC city tax</a>. However, New York's top state rate of 10.9% only applies to income over $25 million, while California's 13.3% kicks in at just $1 million. This lower threshold means that far more California taxpayers are affected by the top rate than in New York.</p>

        <p>New Jersey presents another interesting comparison. Its top rate of 10.75% on income over $1 million is lower than California's, and New Jersey does not impose a disability insurance tax as steep as California's SDI. Hawaii, despite its top rate of 11%, has a lower cost of entry into its highest brackets and a generally lower cost of living than coastal California. Minnesota's top rate of 9.85% is substantial but still well below California's. What sets California apart from all these states is the combination of high income tax rates with high costs for housing, gasoline, utilities, and groceries. A worker might face a similar statutory tax rate in New Jersey, but the overall cost of living in northern New Jersey, while high, is generally lower than San Francisco or Los Angeles.</p>

        <p>For workers considering relocation to reduce their tax burden, states like Texas, Florida, Nevada, and Washington offer zero state income tax. Our <a href="/take-home-comparison/">take-home pay comparison tool</a> lets you see exactly how much more you would keep by living in a no-income-tax state versus California. However, it is worth noting that states without income taxes often compensate through higher property taxes, sales taxes, or other fees. The <a href="/guides/moving-to-a-no-income-tax-state/">guide to moving to a no-income-tax state</a> covers the full range of trade-offs involved in such a decision.</p>

        <h2 id="prop-13-property-taxes">Proposition 13 and California Property Taxes</h2>
        <p>One area where California taxpayers catch a meaningful break is property taxes, thanks to Proposition 13, which voters approved in 1978. This landmark ballot measure capped the property tax rate at 1% of a property's assessed value at the time of purchase, with annual assessment increases limited to no more than 2% per year regardless of how much the property's market value rises. In practice, this means that a homeowner who purchased a house in 1990 for $200,000 might be paying property taxes on an assessed value of around $400,000 even if the home is now worth $1.5 million on the open market.</p>

        <p>Proposition 13 has created enormous disparities between long-term homeowners and recent buyers. A family that bought a home in a desirable neighborhood decades ago might pay $4,000 to $5,000 in annual property taxes, while their neighbor who purchased an identical house last year could be paying $15,000 to $20,000. This dynamic has been widely debated, with supporters arguing that Prop 13 protects elderly and fixed-income homeowners from being taxed out of their homes, and critics contending that it shifts the tax burden onto newer and younger homeowners while reducing revenue for local schools and services. For a detailed analysis of how property taxes work in California versus other states, our <a href="/property-tax-calculator/">property tax calculator</a> provides state-by-state comparisons.</p>

        <h2 id="living-in-california-on-various-salaries">Living in California on Various Salary Levels</h2>
        <p>The experience of living in California varies dramatically depending on where in the state you reside and how much you earn. A salary of $60,000 might provide a comfortable lifestyle in Fresno or Bakersfield, where median rents are well below $2,000 per month, but that same income would leave a worker struggling in San Francisco, where a one-bedroom apartment frequently exceeds $3,000. After federal taxes, California state taxes, SDI, and FICA deductions, a $60,000 salary in California yields roughly $46,000 to $48,000 in annual take-home pay, or about $3,800 to $4,000 per month. In the state's most expensive metros, that barely covers rent and basic necessities.</p>

        <p>At $100,000, the calculus shifts somewhat. Take-home pay after all taxes lands in the range of $73,000 to $76,000 annually, depending on filing status and deductions. This salary provides a solid middle-class life in Sacramento, San Diego, or the Inland Empire, where housing costs are meaningfully lower than in the Bay Area. However, in San Francisco or Silicon Valley, $100,000 is considered moderate income by local standards, and many employers in those areas adjust compensation accordingly. The <a href="/salary-calculator/">salary calculator</a> can help translate your gross pay into a realistic monthly budget based on your filing status and location.</p>

        <p>Crossing into the $150,000 to $200,000 range puts a California worker into the 9.3% state bracket, and the combined federal and state marginal rate begins to feel substantial. At $200,000, a single filer in California will pay approximately $13,000 to $14,000 in state income tax alone, plus roughly $2,200 in SDI, on top of $35,000 or more in federal income tax and FICA. Still, this income level enables home purchases in many parts of the state, significant retirement contributions through a <a href="/401k-calculator/">401(k)</a> or <a href="/roth-ira-calculator/">Roth IRA</a>, and a generally comfortable lifestyle even in expensive coastal cities.</p>

        <p>For high earners at $500,000 or above, California's tax bite becomes severe. The state income tax alone on $500,000 of taxable income exceeds $45,000, and the Mental Health Services Tax adds a further $5,000 for every million above the threshold. Workers at this level often employ sophisticated tax planning strategies, including maximizing pre-tax retirement contributions, timing stock option exercises, and structuring deferred compensation arrangements. Some choose to establish residency in a lower-tax state while maintaining business ties to California, though the Franchise Tax Board is notoriously aggressive about auditing individuals who claim to have left the state while retaining significant connections. Understanding your full tax picture at any income level starts with running your numbers through this calculator and comparing the results with other states using our <a href="/income-tax-calculator/">income tax calculator</a>.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </Fragment>
</CalculatorLayout>
